## 4. Token validation at call time (the hot path)

<!-- guidance: This is the section the reviewer maps directly to their
attack requests. Document the exact ordered checks a request passes between
"bearer token arrives" and "first business query executes": lookup form
(hash compare? signature verify? introspection?), expiry check, revocation
check, bound-principal liveness check (user still exists/active/not deleted),
and — critically for multi-tenant systems — WHERE the tenant/user context gets
bound for the request (e.g. session variables, connection GUCs, request
context). A field-tested pattern worth imitating: tokens stored only as
SHA-256 hashes so the lookup is hash-equality against a unique-constrained
column and no plaintext exists at rest; note WHY a fast hash rather than a
password KDF is correct for high-entropy random tokens (no brute-force
surface; per-call KDF cost would degrade the hot path) — reviewers ask. -->

