## 5. Access control at call time — the enforcement layers

<!-- guidance: One subsection per INDEPENDENT layer, in the order they
execute. Independence is the claim reviewers test: bypassing layer 1 must not
defeat layer 2. Typical layering for an MCP server: (a) per-tool OAuth scope
gate — applied at BOTH tools/list and tools/call, because a client can call a
tool by name it never saw listed; (b) application role filter (RBAC); (c)
tenant isolation at the data layer (e.g. Postgres row-level security keyed on
a per-request binding — state whether the runtime DB role can bypass it);
(d) per-user visibility within a tenant (own-records / subtree filters).
For each layer: what enforces it, where in code, what happens on failure, and
the negative test that proves it (test file::test name). A layer without a
test is a claim, not a control. -->

